# Data Preprocessing
df = df.dropna()  # Dropping rows with missing values

# Define independent variables (X) and dependent variables (Y)
X = df.drop(['Life expectancy ', 'Life_expectancy_category'], axis=1)  # Drop target columns
y_continuous = df['Life expectancy ']  # For OLS
y_binary = df['Life_expectancy_category'].apply(lambda x: 1 if x == 'High' else 0)  # For Logit

# Add a constant to the independent variables (for intercept)
X = sm.add_constant(X)

The Status features in (X) is not either a float type or an integer type so it is impossible to feed this feature as an input to Regression model or else logistic Regression model. So we need to perform any one of the following - onehot encoding, binary encoding, label encoding. In this approach we are following label encoding where we are assigning 0 for developing and 1 for Developed.

from statsmodels.stats.outliers_influence import variance_inflation_factor

# Select only numerical features for VIF calculation
numerical_X = X.select_dtypes(include=[np.number])

# Calculate VIF for each independent variable
vif = pd.DataFrame()
vif["VIF Factor"] = [variance_inflation_factor(numerical_X.values, i) for i in range(numerical_X.shape[1])]
vif["features"] = numerical_X.columns

# Display the VIF values
print(vif)

# Identify variables with high VIF (e.g., > 5 or 10)
high_vif_variables = vif[vif["VIF Factor"] > 5]["features"].tolist()

All the requisite actions are taken to address multicollinearity since it affects the model’s efficiency and its results explicitly. Because the target or dependent variable is Life Expectancy, it is important that the independent variables do not co-vary strongly with each other in order to acquire realistic results.

It is easy to sum up or aggregate identical parameters for example, thinness 1-19 years and thinness 5-9 years. Lastly, I am again computing VIF to check that multicollinearity problem is now resolved and that the model is now built with those variables which best predict Life Expectancy.

# OLS Regression

y_pred_ols = ols_model.predict(X)

# Calculate RMSE and R-squared

Report¶

According to the statistics generated these are the following interpretations we can do -

  1. Year, thinness 1-19 years and thinness 5-9 years are non-significant variables.
  2. Remaining features have an acceptatble p-value and are significant.
  3. The small RMSE(4.1310) values indicates an better model performance and average deviation of predicted value from the actual value.
  4. As interpreted from the correlation plot, the condition number also supports the statement that there is strong multicolineartiy existing (predictors are highly correlated)
  5. R-squared values(0.8112) indicates that that 81.12% of the of the variance in the dependent varaible is explained.
  6. Overall this model seems to be a good fit to the given data.

Health Factors: Under five deaths, HIV/AIDS and Adult mortality have a negative and significant correlation with life expectancy. Economic Factors: GDP and income composition have a positive correlation with life expectancy; this re-emphasizes the fact that resource is an essential factor when it comes to improvement of the health of the societies. Educational Impact: Education plays critical role in life expectancy as revealed by schooling. Healthcare and Immunization: Spending on health control through immunization such as the diphtheria vaccination and the fight against killer diseases such as Hepatitis B and HIV/AIDS is central in raising life length.

The results of the regression model developed using the OLS estimates give a different angle to the analysis of the life expectancy determinants. The model is very robust, accounting for over 81 % of the variability in life expectancy. They are adult mortality, under five deaths, HIV/AIDS, schooling, and income composition labeled as factors that are significantly predictive of these countries. But there is an issue of multicollinearity-probably affecting the reliability of some of the coefficients based on the high condition number. It thus requires further tuning, and predictors with extremely high correlation.

Report¶

The logistic regression output indicates the relationship between several predictors and the binary dependent variable, life expectancy category. The Log-Likelihood (-813.74) Indicates the fit of the model, with improvement over the null log-likelihood (-2036.5). The likelihood ratio test (LLR p-value = 0.000) confirms that the model overall is significant. The model correctly classifies 88.15% of the observations. From P values Year, Status, Hepatitis B, Measles, BMI, Diphtheria, GDP these predictors do not show statistically significant relationships with life expectancy categories. From the above obtained results shows a good fit, with about 60% of the variability in the dependent variable explained by the predictors.

from sklearn.metrics import precision_score, recall_score

precision_logit = precision_score(y_binary, y_pred_logit_class)
recall_logit = recall_score(y_binary, y_pred_logit_class)

print(f"Logit Precision: {precision_logit}")
print(f"Logit Recall: {recall_logit}")

Logit Precision: 0.8648825065274152
Logit Recall: 0.9038199181446112

Precision (0.8648): This assesses the result of the percentage of correctly identified positive or percentage of correctly classification of the positive class observed from the models. In this case, out of 100 instances which the model has predicted to be positive, only 86.61 percent of those instances are actually positive. A measure of accuracy is critical when the price of a simple mistake that is close to the true value is high (for example, diseases or fraud).

Recall (0.9038): This measures how well the model Liên khuếch đại and classify the true positive instances out of the actual positive worthIDD. Specificity: The true positive instances show that 90.38% of the actual positives were predicted as positive. As with most diagnostic tests, recall is useful when the cost of false negatives is very high, and an example is when one misses a disease diagnosis.
